title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>(Wielendt) Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|G|=p^{a}m]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\geq 0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\nmid  m]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega =\{A\subseteq  G\mid  |A|=p^{a}\}]]></fr:tex>. We see that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> acts on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> by right multiplication. Since this is an action, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> is partitioned into orbits, and so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |]]></fr:tex> is the sum of the orbit sizes.</fr:p>
<fr:p>But
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[|\Omega |=\binom {p^{a}m}{p^{a}}\equiv  m\not \equiv 0\pmod {p},]]></fr:tex>
and so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Omega |]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists some orbit <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> is not divisible by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X\in \mathcal {O}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H=G_{X}]]></fr:tex> be the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-004C.xml"
addr="gr-004C"
title="Stabilizer">Stabilizer</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|=|G|/|H|]]></fr:tex> by the <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-004G.xml"
addr="gr-004G"
title="Orbit-Stabilizer theorem">Orbit-Stabilizer theorem</fr:link>, and since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> does not divide <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|\mathcal {O}|]]></fr:tex> but <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|G|]]></fr:tex>, we must conclude <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|]]></fr:tex>, and in particular <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}\leq |H|]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> stabilizes <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> under right multiplication, we see if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[xH\subseteq  X]]></fr:tex>, and then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|=|xH|\leq |X|=p^{a}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p^{a}\leq |H|\leq  p^{a}]]></fr:tex>, we must have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|H|=p^{a}]]></fr:tex>, and this is a Sylow subgroup of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> as desired.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
